Pedigrees were available from 46 Burmese cats (12 brown, four brown tortie, three chocolate, two cream, 11 blue, eight lilac, three red and three undisclosed colour). Dates of birth of affected cats in this series ranged from 1984 to 2008. Analysis revealed common ancestors on both the paternal and maternal sides of all the affected cats' pedigrees. Some cats were obviously very closely related (Fig 4
)a, b, c
and many Burmese breeders made anecdotal comments regarding affected litters or relatives suggesting a hereditary tendency. However, information on affected or unaffected relatives is currently too incomplete to make conclusions about the mode of inheritance.
